topics that they don't know about. All right. Back to the slides.

00:42:50.600 --> 00:42:56.520
Okay. Now, to install it, here's how it works. So, in VS Code, go to the extensions.

00:42:57.479 --> 00:43:04.280
And I'm sorry. You click on this thing for extensions. Type in Shiny up here. Click on

00:43:04.280 --> 00:43:08.840
this Shiny thing that will pop up. It should be at the top of the list. And then click on install.

00:43:09.719 --> 00:43:14.760
And it will install the it should install the latest version of the Shiny extension for you.

00:43:16.120 --> 00:43:22.919
And it does require a GitHub Copilot subscription. All right. And then to use it, make sure it's in

00:43:22.919 --> 00:43:28.280
ask mode. This is a very new feature that they just added to their interface within the last

00:43:28.280 --> 00:43:37.560
week. And then say at Shiny and ask it to do things. Okay. So, how is it different from the

00:43:37.560 --> 00:43:42.360
web version of Shiny Assistant? Well, it uses a GitHub Copilot subscription. That's a very

00:43:42.360 --> 00:43:49.560
important difference. I know many people have it already. And one thing that comes along with that

00:43:49.560 --> 00:43:56.120
is that Copilot has an intellectual property indemnity that's provided by GitHub and Microsoft.

00:43:56.760 --> 00:44:03.159
So, for many organizations, that's important. The Shiny app can use local resources like

00:44:03.159 --> 00:44:10.760
file on disk, data on disk. It can use network resources. The Assistant can modify existing apps.

00:44:10.760 --> 00:44:17.800
And it knows about new Shiny features like AI chat and brand.yaml. So, comparing to other

00:44:17.800 --> 00:44:25.399
coding assistants, it's installed as a VS Code extension like many other of these coding

00:44:25.399 --> 00:44:29.959
assistants. And it integrates with Copilot. You just type in at Shiny. You don't have to

00:44:29.959 --> 00:44:37.560
subscribe. You don't have to get API keys for OpenAI or Anthropic. The system prompt is

00:44:37.560 --> 00:44:41.639
customized with Shiny knowledge. That's what makes it work. And it knows about the latest Shiny

00:44:41.639 --> 00:44:48.199
developments. But it's also not as agentic as some of these AI coding assistants. Some of these

00:44:48.199 --> 00:44:52.040
AI coding assistants can go out and just read a whole bunch of files and change a whole bunch of

00:44:52.040 --> 00:44:58.120
stuff. And Shiny Assistant can do a little bit of that, but not as much as these tools that are

00:44:58.120 --> 00:45:07.320
built for that specific purpose. Okay. All right. So, that's it. You know, we've talked about writing

00:45:07.320 --> 00:45:13.800
Shiny apps that use AI, using AI tools to build Shiny applications, and how these

00:45:13.800 --> 00:45:18.520
conversations with LLMs work. So, I hope you all learned a lot from this and

00:45:20.520 --> 00:45:24.840
are, you know, excited to use Shiny with AI. And thanks for listening.

00:45:27.320 --> 00:45:32.120
Thank you very much, Winston. We have plenty of questions from the audience.

00:45:32.120 --> 00:45:38.439
We might lose some context. So, I kindly ask authors that, if we struggle to answer, to put

00:45:38.439 --> 00:45:44.280
some more context in the chat. So, let's start with Mateo. Does this increase the token cost

00:45:44.280 --> 00:45:49.399
because each request compounds? Yes. That is definitely the case.

00:45:50.520 --> 00:45:55.959
Every time you send a request, you know, each time you're sending a larger and larger payload

00:45:56.840 --> 00:46:02.919
to the server. And that is just how they work. Yeah. That's unavoidable. I mean,

00:46:02.919 --> 00:46:07.399
there are techniques that people use. Like, they might ask an LLM, hey, summarize the previous,

00:46:07.399 --> 00:46:10.600
you know, the previous steps in the conversation for future use. And so,

00:46:10.600 --> 00:46:13.399
the LLM can do that. And you use that summarized version later on.

00:46:15.479 --> 00:46:21.000
Okay. Extending on this question, if we have this big payload in the system prompt,

00:46:21.080 --> 00:46:26.760
is it also including to the total cost of the tokens? Yes. That definitely counts as well.

00:46:27.719 --> 00:46:36.360
But, you know, Anthropic has a prompt caching mechanism where you can cache prompts, like a

00:46:36.360 --> 00:46:41.879
conversation up to a certain point. And if it sees, like, another conversation that has that same

00:46:43.159 --> 00:46:48.439
stuff in the beginning, then it'll draw it from the cache and it costs, like, I think it's,

00:46:48.439 --> 00:46:52.760
like, a tenth of what it normally would cost. And OpenAI does some caching as well. Their

00:46:52.760 --> 00:46:58.840
mechanism is a little different. But, yes. If you have a very large system prompt and you keep

00:46:58.840 --> 00:47:06.120
sending over and over again, it can add up for costs. Okay. Zuhai was asking, is there a limit

00:47:06.120 --> 00:47:13.959
to how far back into the conversation it can look? Yeah. So, most... Okay. So, the best,

00:47:14.520 --> 00:47:19.399
well, the state-of-the-art models these days, you know, they have a limit of, like,

00:47:19.399 --> 00:47:24.919
about 128,000 tokens for OpenAI, 200,000 tokens for Anthropic. And a token is...

00:47:27.399 --> 00:47:34.760
Oh, gosh. A token is, like, a part of a word, typically. So, let's say it's, like,

00:47:35.320 --> 00:47:38.760
kind of translates to maybe typically around about five characters on average, I believe,

00:47:38.760 --> 00:47:48.280
is the correct number for that. And so, there's a limit to how far back you can go. And even,

00:47:48.280 --> 00:47:54.040
you know, even if all of your information fits in that context, the LLMs are not

00:47:54.040 --> 00:47:59.000
perfect at recalling all that information. Especially, like, the Google Gemini models

00:47:59.000 --> 00:48:04.280
have context lengths of, like, a million or two million tokens. And my understanding is that

00:48:04.280 --> 00:48:10.919
when you're getting up to that size, the recall of the stuff in those prompts is not always very good.

00:48:13.399 --> 00:48:16.600
It might relate to the Josh question. As the conversation continues,

00:48:16.600 --> 00:48:20.199
building a longer history, is there an increased potential in hallucinations?

00:48:23.080 --> 00:48:30.280
I don't think there's an increased potential for hallucinations, in my experience. It might

00:48:30.280 --> 00:48:36.360
not remember everything perfectly in that history. But I don't think it makes it more

00:48:36.360 --> 00:48:41.800
likely to just make things up. So, you know... But although when it does happen, that is kind

00:48:41.800 --> 00:48:47.159
of alarming. Like, when, you know, like, chatbots just make up stuff, like, URLs that don't exist.

00:48:47.159 --> 00:48:50.360
And sometimes you don't realize that until you're well into a project. And you're like,

00:48:50.360 --> 00:48:53.399
oh, wait. This is all completely made up.

00:48:54.360 --> 00:49:01.399
Right. Stephen asks, how do you deal with preventing accidental exposure of API keys?

00:49:03.560 --> 00:49:08.360
So, typically... Well, that's actually one more reason we didn't have ShinyLive,

00:49:09.080 --> 00:49:13.080
on the web version of ShinyLive, talk to these AI LLM providers.

00:49:13.320 --> 00:49:23.320
LLM providers. Because the API keys, those should be stored on the server. And the server,

00:49:23.320 --> 00:49:29.639
like the server that's running Python, that server goes and talks to, you know, talks to the LLM

00:49:29.639 --> 00:49:36.520
endpoint. And that server... I mean, it's common practice for the server side of these applications,

00:49:36.520 --> 00:49:40.199
of all sorts of applications, to have various secrets, like API keys and things like that.

00:49:40.199 --> 00:49:47.080
And you treat these in just the same way. But you don't usually put those API keys,

00:49:47.639 --> 00:49:55.560
send those to a web browser. So, yeah. Because if you sent your API key to, like, your user's

00:49:56.439 --> 00:49:59.879
web browser, then they could just use your API key for whatever. And you don't want to do that.

00:50:02.040 --> 00:50:07.800
Absolutely. James' question. Llama Force card has a 10 million context window.

00:50:08.520 --> 00:50:13.560
Could you, in theory, pass a GitHub repo into the system prompt and have the module understand the

00:50:13.560 --> 00:50:20.360
entire repo? Yeah. I mean, there are... And there's tools that help do this. One of them is,

00:50:20.360 --> 00:50:28.760
it's a JavaScript project called RepoMix. And people do that sort of thing. I don't know. I

00:50:28.760 --> 00:50:33.239
haven't used, you know, I haven't used Llama Force Scout. But again, my understanding is that when

00:50:33.239 --> 00:50:37.399
you get to very long context lengths, they're not going to have perfect recall. But they will learn

00:50:37.399 --> 00:50:42.919
something from it. Like, if you want to, you know, probably if you do that and then, you know,

00:50:42.919 --> 00:50:46.679
you ask some questions about it, it will be able to answer them. But perhaps not. It might not

00:50:46.679 --> 00:50:53.800
remember every single little thing that was provided in the system prompt, though. But,

00:50:53.800 --> 00:50:58.439
you know, sorry. I have to add one more thing. Really important thing. Working with these LLMs,

00:50:58.439 --> 00:51:06.199
it's a very empirical process. Like, you don't know what they can and can't do until you try it.

00:51:06.199 --> 00:51:11.719
Sometimes we think they can't do something and that seems hard. But you try it and they can't.

00:51:11.719 --> 00:51:15.000
And the reverse happens. Sometimes you think they should be able to do something very simple,

00:51:15.000 --> 00:51:23.399
like adding numbers. And they can't do that. So, yeah. And it changes also with new models,

00:51:23.399 --> 00:51:29.399
right? Something that worked for you before. It makes it harder to program against them. Yeah.

00:51:30.120 --> 00:51:36.520
Okay. Phil, we ask, does it mean you won't need to send the documentation inside the prompt in

00:51:36.520 --> 00:51:43.719
the future when the models are updated? Yeah. I mean, hopefully. I don't think,

00:51:43.719 --> 00:51:49.719
you know, hopefully they'll learn enough about, you know, Shiny, Shiny for Python, all this

00:51:49.719 --> 00:51:54.679
Shiny chat stuff. Hopefully the training data, their training data will be updated and they

00:51:54.679 --> 00:51:58.360
will learn enough about it that we don't have to supply a ton of that documentation to them.

00:52:00.360 --> 00:52:04.120
Like, they don't, you know, for the system prompts, they write very good JavaScript and

00:52:04.120 --> 00:52:09.639
React code, these LLMs. And they don't stick that in the system prompt. There's just so much

00:52:09.639 --> 00:52:13.879
good training data out there that they can just do it. So, I mean, we probably won't get to that

00:52:13.879 --> 00:52:18.360
level of popularity, but hopefully it'll be good enough that they'll do a decent job.

00:52:19.719 --> 00:52:27.399
Right. Thanks. And the next one, do the web chat interfaces work in the same way described earlier,

00:52:27.479 --> 00:52:32.679
stateless server side and sending the entire conversation history with every message?

00:52:32.679 --> 00:52:37.399
Yes. Yep. So, the web chat interfaces, there's the LLM part of it. And then there's like this

00:52:38.120 --> 00:52:43.639
web application server, that layer that's built around it. So, that, you know, that web application

00:52:43.639 --> 00:52:48.520
layer will save like previous conversations that you can go back to. They'll provide some tools,

00:52:48.520 --> 00:52:55.800
like searching the web. So, that's, that is the, like, the chat GPT web page or website.

00:52:55.800 --> 00:53:02.840
But the chat GPT API that you can talk to in the way that I showed,

00:53:03.479 --> 00:53:13.639
that doesn't have any of those features. So, yeah. So, the web application does a lot of

00:53:13.639 --> 00:53:17.399
these things that I was talking about, like building up the message history and things like that.

00:53:18.280 --> 00:53:25.560
Mm-hmm. Sebastian asks, can you show us how to update the system prompt with information about

